
ðŸŸ¦ 1. cat /etc/os-release â€” OS Name & Version

This file contains system identification data for all Linux distributions.

##Usage


cat /etc/os-release


##Typical Output


NAME="Rocky Linux"
VERSION="9.3 (Blue Onyx)"
ID="rocky"
VERSION_ID="9.3"
PRETTY_NAME="Rocky Linux 9.3 (Blue Onyx)"


##Explanation of Fields

| Field            | Meaning                    |
| ---------------- | -------------------------- |
| NAME           | OS name                    |
| VERSION        | OS version (major + minor) |
| ID             | Short OS identifier        |
| VERSION_ID     | Numeric version            |
| PRETTY_NAME    | Human-readable OS name     |
| HOME_URL       | Official website           |
| SUPPORT_URL    | Support page               |
| BUG_REPORT_URL | Bug reporting page         |

> No command options â€” its just a readable file.

---

ðŸŸ¦ 2. cat /etc/redhat-release â€” RHEL Based OS Version

For RHEL, Rocky, AlmaLinux, CentOS.

##Usage


cat /etc/redhat-release


##Example Output


Rocky Linux release 9.3 (Blue Onyx)


> Again, no options â€” it is just a version file specific to RHEL-family systems.

---

ðŸŸ¦ 3. lsb_release â€” Linux Standard Base Information

Works on Ubuntu, Debian, Rocky (after installing redhat-lsb-core), etc.

##Usage


lsb_release [OPTION]


##All Important Options

| Option | Description                   | Example           |
| ------ | ----------------------------- | ----------------- |
| -a   | Show all LSB information  | lsb_release -a  |
| -d   | Show OS description           | lsb_release -d  |
| -i   | Show distributor ID           | lsb_release -i  |
| -r   | OS release number             | lsb_release -r  |
| -c   | Codename (e.g., focal, jammy) | lsb_release -c  |
| -s   | Short output (compact)        | lsb_release -ds |
| -v   | LSB version compatibility     | lsb_release -v  |

##Example Output (lsb_release -a)


Distributor ID: Ubuntu
Description:    Ubuntu 22.04.3 LTS
Release:        22.04
Codename:       jammy


---

ðŸŸ¦ 4. dmesg | head â€” Boot Messages

##What is dmesg?

dmesg prints kernel and boot-related messages.

##Basic Usage


dmesg | head


Shows the first few boot messages.

##Useful Options

| Option       | Description                       | Example                  |
| ------------ | --------------------------------- | ------------------------ |
| dmesg      | Show all kernel logs              | dmesg                  |
| -T         | Convert timestamps to human time  | dmesg -T               |
| -k         | Kernel messages only              | dmesg -k               |
| -l <level> | Filter severity (err, warn, info) | dmesg -l err           |
| -w         | Watch live kernel messages        | dmesg -w               |
| --level=   | Multi-level filter                | dmesg --level=err,warn |

##Severity Levels (Important for Admins)

 emerg
 alert
 crit
 err
 warn
 notice
 info
 debug

##Examples

Show only errors:


dmesg -l err


Watch kernel logs live:


dmesg -w


Readable timestamps:


dmesg -T


---

ðŸŸ¦ 5. journalctl -b â€” Boot Logs (systemd)

journalctl reads the systemd journal logs.

##Show current boot logs


journalctl -b


##Show previous boot logs

(If multiple boots exist)


journalctl -b -1
journalctl -b -2


---

##Important Journalctl Options for Admins

| Option          | Description                      | Example                                 |
| --------------- | -------------------------------- | --------------------------------------- |
| -b            | Logs from current boot           | journalctl -b                         |
| -k            | Kernel logs only                 | journalctl -k                         |
| -u <service>  | Show logs for a specific service | journalctl -u sshd                    |
| -f            | Follow logs live (like tail -f)  | journalctl -f                         |
| --since       | Logs from specific time          | journalctl --since "2 hours ago"      |
| --until       | Logs up to specific time         | journalctl --until "2025-01-30 14:00" |
| -p <level>    | Filter by priority               | journalctl -p err                     |
| -r            | Reverse output (newest first)    | journalctl -r                         |
| --disk-usage  | Check journal log disk usage     | journalctl --disk-usage               |
| --vacuum-size | Cleanup journal logs             | journalctl --vacuum-size=500M         |
| --vacuum-time | Delete logs older than X         | journalctl --vacuum-time=30d          |

##Priority Levels (important!)

 0 = emerg
 1 = alert
 2 = crit
 3 = err
 4 = warning
 5 = notice
 6 = info
 7 = debug

##Examples

Show only error logs:


journalctl -p err


Show logs for SSH service:


journalctl -u sshd


Live logs:


journalctl -f


